Configuration Properties allow you to read values from application.properties or application.yml and inject them into Java classes. This keeps configuration separate from the application code.
Spring Boot provides:
@Value (for single values) 
@ConfigurationProperties (for groups of related properties)


Without Configuration Properties
String dbUser="root";String dbPassword="root";String url="jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/javadb";
Problems:
Hardcoded values 
Difficult to change 
Different code for Dev/Testing/Production 
With Configuration Properties
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/javadbspring.datasource.username=rootspring.datasource.password=root
Simply modify the properties file.
No Java code changes.




